      "verified_answer": "C",
      "set_the_stage": "A 65‑year‑old fair‑skinned man presents with a long‑standing, solitary, 0.5 cm scaly plaque on the forearm. Shave biopsy demonstrates intraepithelial squamous cell carcinoma (Bowen’s disease) with positive/close margins, indicating incomplete excision.",
      "highlight_excellence": "The key teaching point recognized is that Bowen’s disease, although confined to the epidermis, carries a risk of progression to invasive SCC. Incomplete excision mandates definitive treatment to achieve histologically clear margins, and the answer choice C correctly recommends re‑excision with appropriate margin control and primary closure or reconstruction.",
      "address_gaps": "• Option A (wide excision + sentinel node biopsy) is unnecessary because there is no evidence of invasion or nodal involvement in intraepithelial disease. \n• Option B (local radiation) is reserved for patients who are poor surgical candidates or have lesions in anatomically challenging sites; it is not first‑line for a small, easily resectable forearm lesion. \n• Option D (no further treatment) would leave residual dysplastic cells in place, risking progression. \n• Option E (topical 5‑FU) is an acceptable alternative for patients who refuse surgery, but surgical excision provides immediate histologic confirmation of clearance and is preferred when feasible.",
      "review_guidelines": "Current NCCN and AAD guidelines for Bowen’s disease advise complete surgical excision with 4‑6 mm margins for lesions ≤2 cm when anatomically possible. When excision is not feasible, topical chemotherapeutic agents (5‑FU, imiquimod), cryotherapy, or photodynamic therapy are acceptable alternatives. Sentinel lymph node biopsy is not indicated for intraepithelial SCC.",
      "plan": "1. Schedule a re‑excision of the forearm lesion with 4‑6 mm clinical margins, using a technique that allows for primary closure or a simple local flap if needed. \n2. Send the excised specimen for permanent histopathology to confirm clear margins. \n3. If margins remain positive, consider a second excision or alternative modalities (e.g., topical 5‑FU). \n4. Educate the patient on sun protection and skin self‑examination. \n5. Arrange follow‑up visits at 3‑month intervals for the first year, then every 6‑12 months, to monitor for recurrence or new lesions."
