      "review_guidelines": "1. **Diagnosis:** EHBDC is often diagnosed incidentally on imaging performed for other conditions.  Consider it in patients with unexplained jaundice, elevated liver enzymes, or biliary sludge. 2. **Staging:**  Staging is crucial due to the aggressive nature of the disease.  MRI and CT scans are primary imaging modalities. 3. **Treatment:** Surgical resection (Whipple procedure, Roux-en-Y) is the optimal treatment when feasible. Adjuvant therapy is frequently employed. 4. **Prognosis:** EHBDC has a very poor prognosis, often due to late diagnosis and lack of effective systemic therapies. 5. **Risk Factors:**  Cholangiocarcinoma (the most common type of EHBDC) is associated with primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC), chronic liver disease, and genetic mutations.",
