      "verified_answer": "B",
      "set_the_stage": "Radiation therapy relies on causing double-strand DNA breaks. The cell's ability to repair this damage varies dramatically across the cell cycle.",
      "highlight_excellence": "During the M phase (Mitosis), the DNA is tightly coiled into chromosomes and the cell is actively dividing. If radiation shatters the DNA here, the damage is immediately fatal to the cell because it bypasses the normal checkpoint repair mechanisms. Conversely, in the S phase, active repair enzymes easily fix the radiation damage.",
